<HEADLINE>
<P>
PHILIPPINE PLOTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thank you for the excellent article on the former Marcos crony Eduardo Murphy 
Cojuangco Jr. (Part A, Dec. 26). 
</P>
<P>
One does not have to be a genius to conclude which Filipino businessmen and 
politicians were most likely to have been involved in plotting and financing 
the latest attempt to topple the democratically elected Corazon Aquino 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
As your own newspaper reported, ordinary soldiers were openly paid $15 a day 
during the height of the stand-off in the Makati financial district. Reports 
from the islands also tell of payments in millions of pesos to the rebel armed 
forces officers. 
</P>
<P>
But one thing that these businessmen and politicians seem to have forgotten are 
historical lessons, ranging from Adolf Hitler to Manuel Noriega. Once these 
types of people are in the saddle, among the first that they will eliminate are 
the very ones who helped them seize power. 
</P>
<P>
The other disturbing development during the latest coup attempt was the rebels' 
breaking of the time-honored code that the physical safety of the country's 
president not be jeopardized. There is a saying in the Philippines which 
roughly translates thus: "There is no limit to revenge. . . ." Now that the 
code has been broken, there is no telling what the fanatical elements of the 
other side will attempt to do. That can only lead to more misery for ordinary 
Filipinos. 
</P>
<P>
EUGENE V. CORAZO 
</P>
<P>
Granada Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
