<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHEN FRONT OF THE LINE IS BACK OF THE BUS; 
</P>
<P>
RACISM: A MAN HAILING A CAB AT LA GUARDIA MIGHT BE A STAR, A HERO, EVEN THE 
NEXT MAYOR -- BUT IF HE'S BLACK, HE'LL WALK. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS, Christopher Matthews writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Sir!" the black man running the cab stand was saying. 
</P>
<P>
"Sir!" he repeated, finally catching my eye. "Would you mind standing up here 
for a minute?" 
</P>
<P>
Instantly, I knew exactly what he was talking about. I knew the problem. I also 
knew the trick the big, open-faced fellow had in mind. 
</P>
<P>
The scene: New York's La Guardia Airport. The time: a few minutes before 10 
p.m. New Year's Eve. Like the other passengers just off the Trump Shuttle from 
Washington, I had been waiting in the cab line without success. Cab after cab 
would make the turn from the expressway, drive slowly past our cab stand, then 
swerve away. 
</P>
<P>
I could see exactly what was happening. The cab drivers, one after another, 
were taking one look at the faces of those just-arrived passengers at the Trump 
Shuttle cab line, then speeding up and heading over to the better pickings at 
the Delta terminal. 
</P>
<P>
Why? Most of the passengers waiting in the Trump Shuttle line were black. 
</P>
<P>
I knew this. So did the frustrated guy running the cab stand. I could see it in 
his look when our eyes connected after the 20th or 30th cab had chosen Delta 
over Trump for his choice of fare. He knew what was happening all right. This 
is what went on night after night. Why should it be any different because a 
white man was standing four or five places back in line? 
</P>
<P>
I had almost had enough of this little vignette in American race relations 
circa 1990. After waiting a good 20 minutes, I prepared myself to just bolt the 
hapless Trump line and make the couple-hundred-yard walk to the Delta terminal. 
What was I supposed to do? I was already late. Was I supposed to stand here all 
night just to prove I'm willing to play and suffer by the same rules that 
punish black people? 
</P>
<P>
But something stopped me. Maybe I'd have been marooned there all night, but I 
also couldn't bring myself to just zip over to the Delta terminal. I kept 
flashing on the looks and feelings that would be exchanged by those left 
behind, those watching a white man striding off to his accustomed better 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
"Would you mind standing up here?" 
</P>
<P>
Grabbing my bags, I headed to the front of the line. "I thought that's what was 
going on," I said to the man running the stand. 
</P>
<P>
Then it happened. The very next cab swerved to the left, rejecting the Delta 
terminal and making the wide turn toward those of us who had been waiting 
without hope. 
</P>
<P>
I stepped back and let the group of young black men ahead of me board. 
</P>
<P>
"Thanks," said the man at the stand. 
</P>
<P>
A few days before this, a man named Colin Powell, who happens to be chairman of 
the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, was cheered as the liberator of Panama. A few 
hours later, an easy-going politician named David Dinkins took the oath as 
mayor of New York. The following evening, a wonderful quarterback named Tony 
Rice led the Fighting Irish of Notre Dame to its big Orange Bowl victory over 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
Had they been waiting for a cab at La Guardia Airport New Year's Eve, they 
might still be standing there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010490-0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 157103 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 4, 1990, Thursday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 7; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
277 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ESCAPED INMATE, 3 OTHERS TAKEN IN APARTMENT RAID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One of two men who escaped from custody in October was captured Wednesday in a 
raid of an apartment on 42nd Street, San Diego police said. 
</P>
<P>
Martin Para, 30, and three other people were arrested on suspicion of welfare 
fraud, felony harboring of a fugitive and armed robbery, said Gordon Redding of 
the Police Department. 
</P>
<P>
Para was being held on suspicion of auto theft Oct. 2 when he and Chris Brown, 
31, escaped from a holding area underneath police headquarters, Redding said. 
Brown is still at large. 
</P>
<P>
Para is also known as Martin Velasco, and police believe he is the brother of 
one of the other people arrested Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Redding declined to specify how police were led to the apartment in the 4100 
block of 42nd Street, saying, "We've been receiving tidbits of information and 
sightings here and sightings there." 
</P>
<P>
"Late last night, we received what was pretty well the final piece of the 
puzzle," Redding said. The raid, which took place at 9:15 a.m., involved a 
helicopter and 13 officers. 
</P>
<P>
Eddie Velasco, 26; Sinna Essington, 24, and Esther Gutierrez, 24, were also 
arrested at the apartment, which police believe is rented to Gutierrez. 
Essington and Velasco had outstanding warrants for parole violations, and 
Essington is suspected of being involved with welfare fraud, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Gutierrez was arrested on suspicion of felony harboring of a fugitive and 
misdemeanor possession of narcotics paraphernalia found at the apartment, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
Officers said they found a starter's pistol in a car believed to be Velasco's 
and are investigating possible links between the suspects and robberies in the 
San Diego area since Para's escape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010490-0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 157104 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 4, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 7; Column 4; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
692 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE MONSTER OF 'ZERO DEFECTS' STILL LIVES; 
</P>
<P>
MILITARY: THE INVASION OF PANAMA REVEALED WEAKNESSES IN OUR FORCES' 
CAPABILITIES -- AND IN THE PUBLIC'S OVER-HYPED EXPECTATIONS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HARRY G. SUMMERS JR., Harry G. Summers Jr., a retired Army colonel, held the 
Gen. Douglas MacArthur Chair at the Army War College. He writes a syndicated 
column from Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. military invasion of Panama highlighted some fundamentals that will 
continue to influence the application of American power. First is that Karl von 
Clausewitz's 160-year-old concept of "friction" -- i.e., nothing will ever 
proceed exactly as planned -- is still with us. For example, at Ft. Bragg, 
N.C., the takeoff of elements of the 82nd Airborne Division was delayed by an 
unexpected ice storm; on the opposite coast, at Ft. Ord, Calif., the takeoff of 
elements of the 7th Infantry Division was delayed by dense fog. Despite all the 
advances of modern technology, the caprices of weather still have a major 
effect on the execution of military operations. 
</P>
<P>
And despite the most detailed and precise planning -- and the planning for 
Operation Just Cause was thorough indeed -- mistakes still happen, just as they 
did at the Normandy beachhead 45 years ago. From a military point of view, such 
glitches are to be expected: The best way to deal with friction, Clausewitz 
said, is to anticipate and be prepared for it. But how civilians perceive these 
mistakes may be quite another matter. 
</P>
<P>
The American public has been led into false expectations by the Pentagon brass. 
Trying to build public support, Defense Department bureaucrats discarded 
Clausewitz as inimical to the public relations image they wished to create. 
That was the image of an American military that could conduct flawless 
operations where everything went exactly as planned and where practically no 
one got hurt. 
</P>
<P>
Unwittingly, this "zero defects" mentality created a monster, for "surgical 
precision" became the standard by which the media and the public measured 
military prowess. The successes of the Libyan raid and the Grenada incursion, 
for example, were overshadowed by the "frictions" that denied the perfection 
that Americans had been led to expect. Pentagon powers, realizing they had 
created a false and misleading picture, have since made a concerted effort to 
drive a stake through the heart of the "surgical precision" monster. The 
mythology lives on: Initial media reporting on the Panama invasion once again 
focused on glitches rather than successes. 
</P>
<P>
This is serious business that goes far beyond public-relations glitz. In the 
1990s, when fewer and fewer Americans will have firsthand combat knowledge, the 
false notion that military operations can be "surgical" could have disastrous 
consequences. It could tempt us into actions we would soon regret. Americans 
must be told and understand the bloody and imprecise nature of military force. 
</P>
<P>
Another fundamental highlighted by the Panama invasion is that the United 
States remains a world island that must project its power beyond its borders in 
order to influence international events. With geography education in such 
disrepute that some college students believe the Soviet Union is somewhere in 
Central America, such elementary facts bear repeating. 
</P>
<P>
The first requirement of American military strategy is to get there from here. 
In the Panamanian invasion, that reality was somewhat hidden by the fact that 
airlift alone was able to move most of the combat forces into position. But 
Panama was a special case. Not only was it within flying distance from 
continental military bases, there was also a major logistical support 
foundation already in place. 
</P>
<P>
If, as would be the case in most other projections of American power, that 
support base had had to be established concurrent with the invasion, our lift 
capability would have been severely strained. Taking nothing away from the 
enormous effort put forth by the Military Airlift Command, it still remains a 
fact that America's strategic lift capability is in sad shape. Sealift in 
particular is in shambles as America's maritime fleet continues to shrink, and 
it is sealift that normally moves the majority of oil, ammunition and heavy 
combat arms and equipment. 
</P>
<P>
The lack of such heavy lift could be deadly. Our success in Panamashould not 
blind us to the fact that the lack of sufficient airlift and sealift remains 
our greatest strategic military shortcoming. Correcting that deficiency should 
be one of the major priorities for the 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
