<HEADLINE>
<P>
AFFIRMATIVE ACTION AT SCHOOLS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ian Marantz's misinformed stance on University of California admissions 
policies (Letters, Dec. 27) sadly represents the widespread belief that 
Asian-Americans are considered "affirmative action" students. 
</P>
<P>
At UC Irvine and at all UC campuses, only African-American, Native American and 
Latino applicants fall under the affirmative action program. 
</P>
<P>
As an intermediate step toward an equal-opportunity society, affirmative action 
aims to "balance the ethnic imbalances" that institutions have created to 
ensure that under-represented students are not rejected admission because of 
their color. 
</P>
<P>
One reason Asian-Americans are well represented at UC Irvine and also 
ineligible for affirmative action is their accomplishment in proving their 
academic worth despite all the discriminatory barriers that still exist in 
society. 
</P>
<P>
But now the UC system is turning its back on meritocracy by refusing admission 
to qualified Asian-American students. 
</P>
<P>
Marantz claims that UC Irvine discriminates against white Americans while 
reserving spots for Asian-Americans. How can that be when white and Asian 
students are theoretically admitted under just one criterion -- merit? Yet 
current admission policies prove this untrue. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately for Asians, UC admissions officials are fusing personal merit and 
skin color. Regrettably, the latter wins out in the dominant society, even 
today. 
</P>
<P>
UC admissions now overtly embraces discrimination, once again, in favor of 
whites. By reserving places for white students while rejecting qualified 
(sometimes more qualified) Asian applicants, the university is throwing 
meritocracy out the window. 
</P>
<P>
Let's not revert to the discriminatory sins. Instead, the aim should be a 
color-blind society based upon individual merit. 
</P>
<P>
JANET OTSUKI 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton 
</P>
</TEXT>
