<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: SHEARSON'S LANE QUITS FOLLOWING REALIGNMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jeffrey B. Lane, recently removed as president and chief operating officer of 
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., has resigned from the securities firm. 
</P>
<P>
Lane said he left because he was no longer effective as a result of a 
realignment of the firm's senior management. 
</P>
<P>
"If you're not happy and not enthusiastic, you can't be effective," Lane said, 
explaining why he left Shearson after 20 years with the brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
Before the shake-up in November, Lane had been the No. 2 executive after 
Chairman Peter Cohen. Cohen could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
Lane's resignation from Shearson -- which was effective Friday but revealed 
only after the holiday weekend -- was surprising only in its timing, industry 
observers said. 
</P>
<P>
"The only surprise to me was that he left as quickly as he did," said Perrin 
Long of Lipper Analytical Services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
