<P>
MORNING REPORT: STAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIEL CERONE , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Havel Renaissance: In Britain, interest in the work of Czech 
playwright-turned-president Vaclav Havel has taken a dramatic upswing. Saturday 
night the BBC is airing "Sorry," the television film based on Havel's stage 
play, that stars Michael Crawford and was last broadcast in London in 1978. 
Havel's London-based literary agent said there have been at least 20 requests 
in the last month from people throughout the United Kingdom for the work of 
Havel, Czechoslovakia's first non-Communist president in 41 years. Next 
September, his play "Redevelopment" will be staged in Manchester at the Royal 
Exchange, a major regional theater. DANIEL CERONE 
</P>
