<HEADLINE>
<P>
WESTSIDE DIGEST: WESTWOOD; 
</P>
<P>
STUDENT LAW OFFICE OPENS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The UCLA School of Law is opening a teaching law office where attorneys will 
supervise students working on actual cases for clients. 
</P>
<P>
Located in a newly completed wing of the law school, the campus law office is 
unusual in that it will choose cases primarily for their educational value, a 
UCLA spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
Many of the cases will be small-scale ones that students can complete in a 
single semester. 
</P>
<P>
The school is now looking for a lawyer to head the office and assist in 
teaching other clinical or practical courses offered by the school. Additional 
attorneys will be added to the staff next year. 
</P>
<P>
The office will open on a limited basis this month and will be fully 
operational by the 1990-91 school year. The type of cases emphasized will vary 
from semester to semester, a spokesman said. Initially, all will be civil 
cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
