<P>
BLACK MAN TO HEAD MOBILE POLICE FORCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A veteran of the Detroit police force, Harold L. Johnson Jr., has been hired as 
police chief of Mobile, Ala., the first black police chief in a major Alabama 
city. 
</P>
<P>
A second black man, Reuben Greenberg, was chosen for the post of public safety 
director, which is above that of police chief. Greenberg is chief of police in 
Charleston, S.C. Mobile's population of 200,000 is about 37% black. Lt. Sam 
Cochran, vice president of the Mobile County Law Enforcement Assn., said the 
organization objected to hiring Johnson at more than $65,000 a year because 
starting salary for a uniformed officer is $14,000 a year. Cochran, who is 
white, said race was not a factor in opposition to the hirings. 
</P>
