<P>
SHUTTLE LAUNCHING CLEARED FOR MONDAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The shuttle Columbia was cleared for launching Monday on a 10-day flight, with 
the countdown scheduled to begin today. 
</P>
<P>
It is to put a Navy communications satellite in orbit and retrieve a school 
bus-size satellite used to test the durability of potential spacecraft 
materials. That satellite will drop back into the atmosphere soon if it is not 
retrieved. Liftoff had been scheduled for Dec. 18, but the launch pad at Cape 
Canaveral, Fla., that Columbia is using has been out of service for years, and 
refurbishing took longer than expected. 
