<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY DIGEST: COMPTON; 
</P>
<P>
COUNCIL FAILS TO DECIDE ON RESIDENTIAL DEVELOPMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With one council member absent, the City Council could not agree Tuesday night 
on whether to allow a developer to build 49 apartment units along with 30 
single-family houses near the intersection of Wilmington Avenue and Compton 
Boulevard. Some residents and two council members, Patricia Moore and Maxcy 
Filer, adamantly oppose the apartment portion of the development, saying 
Compton must concentrate on single-family housing to attract middle-income 
residents. 
</P>
<P>
Apartments, according to their detractors, bring low-income renters for whom 
Compton cannot afford to provide services. 
</P>
<P>
Mayor Walter Tucker and Councilwoman Jane Robbins voted to uphold the Planning 
Commission's decision to allow Madison Avenue Properties to build the 
apartments along with the houses. Councilwoman Bernice Woods was absent because 
of illness and the council said it wants to vote on the issue again when 
everyone is present. 
</P>
<P>
The developer is Evan Williams, owner of Dalton Construction Co., which has 
worked on several city projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
