<P>
2ND MISTRIAL IN '82 MURDER CASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A second mistrial was declared today in the case of a British citizen charged 
with murdering four members of a Northridge family who disappeared in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
Superior Court Judge Judith C. Chirlin declared the mistrial after ruling that 
Deputy Public Defender Mark Lessem had a conflict of interest and could no 
longer represent Harvey Rader, 47. 
</P>
<P>
The conflict involved a key prosecution witness, Robert Williams, who had 
recently been represented in a drunken driving case by the public defender's 
office. 
</P>
<P>
Chirlin declared the mistrial on the second day of Rader's second trial. 
Rader's first trial ended in a mistrial Aug. 31 after a Superior Court jury 
deadlocked 11-1 to convict him in the murders of Israeli immigrant Shlomo 
Salomon, 35; his wife, Elaine, and their two children, Michalle, 15, and 
Mitchell, 9. 
</P>
