</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MURRELLS INLET, S.C. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Work has begun on a new house for Mickey Spillane to replace the one destroyed 
by Hurricane Hugo. 
</P>
<P>
The mystery writer has joked that his former home "looked like Godzilla took a 
walk all through that place." 
</P>
<P>
Spillane and his wife, Jane, watched the start of work Wednesday while stakes 
were planted and the areas of the rooms were roped off. 
</P>
<P>
"We're going way up on stilts. It's going to be a bigger house but with more of 
a country flavor and facing the water," Jane Spillane said. 
</P>
<P>
The author has said he waited 19 years to write his latest book, "The Killing 
Man," because "I was doing OK and didn't really need the money." 
</P>
<P>
"After (Hurricane Hugo) I needed the money very badly," he said. 
</P>
